-- 
Crude, Gasoline, Heating Oil Advance on Dollar: Oil Products

-- B y   R i c h a r d   S t u b b e
-- 
2011-05-31T21:24:24Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-31/crude-gasoline-heating-oil-advance-on-dollar-oil-products.html
Crude oil , gasoline and heating oil
increased, rising with equities on signals that the European
Union will approve aid for  Greece , bolstering the euro against
the dollar. Ethanol slipped.  “There are indications that European leaders have found a
way out of the Greek situation that will not cause more upheaval
to the financial markets,” said  Addison Armstrong , director of
market research at Tradition Energy in Stamford,  Connecticut .
“The dollar is weakening as we start the week, the stock market
is rallying and oil is moving higher.”  Crude Oil  Crude oil for July delivery rose $2.11, or 2.1 percent, to
$102.70 a barrel on the  New York Mercantile Exchange . The
intraday high was $103.39. Crude fell 9.9 percent in May, the
first decline after eight straight monthly gains. It has gained
39 percent in the past year.  Crude also advanced with equities worldwide amid
speculation that nations will pledge more aid to Greece. The  Dow
Jones Industrial Average  rose 1 percent to 12,569.79, and the
Standard & Poor’s 500 Index increased 1.1 percent to 1,345.20.  Gasoline  Gasoline for June delivery rose 5.84 cents, or 1.9 percent,
to expire at $3.1504 a gallon on the Nymex. Gasoline dropped 9.1
percent in May and has risen 56 percent in the past year. The
July contract rose 1.9 cents, or 0.6 percent, to $3.0503.  Heating Oil  Heating oil for June delivery gained 6.58 cents, or 2.2
percent, to $3.0563 a gallon. Heating oil dropped 6.1 percent in
May and has gained 54 percent in a year. The July contract rose
5.16 cents, or 1.7 percent, to $3.053.  Ethanol  Denatured ethanol for June delivery dropped 1.8 cents, or
0.7 percent, to $2.642 on the Chicago Board of Trade. Ethanol,
which slipped 0.3 percent in May, has gained 65 percent in the
past year.  Refineries and Transport  Exxon Mobil Corp. is keeping three oil pipeline segments
shut near  Baton Rouge , Louisiana, because of high water. Exxon
said on May 13 it was shutting two 12-inch crude oil lines and a
16-inch products pipeline to reduce risk of damage from flooding
along the Mississippi River.  Valero Energy Corp. has restarted the production units at
its refinery in  Texas  City, Texas, and is moving toward planned
rates after a power loss.  To contact the reporter on this story:
